      <bioghist id="aspace_b5482480cb35554e24e361bf86c8f147">
         <head>BIOGRAPHICAL NOTE</head>
         <p>John Dunton (1659-1732) was a London bookseller during the late seventeenth and early eighteenth centuries. He was the son of Rev. John Dunton (1628-1676). After an apprenticeship from 1674 to 1681, Dunton went into business, primarily dealing in devotional works, sermons, political works, and chapbooks, as well as periodicals. The <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
               <part>Athenian Gazette</part>
            </title> (1691-1697) was Dunton's most successful publication, and it influenced many eighteenth century periodicals. Another notable work was his <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
               <part>Life and Errors of John Dunton, Citizen of London</part>
            </title> (1705), an early example of English autobiography. In his later years Dunton's bookselling business declined with his poor health, and he resorted to pamphleteering to support himself. He died in London on November 24, 1732.</p>
         <p>Stephen Parks was the Curator of the James Marshall and Marie-Louise Osborn Collection at the Beinecke Rare Book &amp; Manuscript Library from 1972 to 2004. Parks's study of John Dunton, <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
               <part>John Dunton and the English Book Trade: A Study of His Career with a Checklist of his Publications</part>
            </title> was published by Garland Publishing, Inc. in 1976.</p>  
      </bioghist>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_772b32ecb81ea3666d4594b56c4b5131">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The Stephen Parks Research Collection on John Dunton consists of correspondence and research materials, spanning the years 1962-1972. The collection documents Stephen Parks's research regarding John Dunton (1659-1732), a London bookseller. The collection is housed in 4 boxes (including 3 oversize boxes), and has been organized into three series: <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
               <part>Research Correspondence</part>
            </title>, <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
               <part>Research Copies</part>
            </title>, and <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
               <part>Writings of Stephen Parks</part>
            </title>.</p>
         <p>
            <ref actuate="onrequest" show="replace" target="ref10">Series I, <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
                  <part>Research Correspondence</part>
               </title> 
            </ref>, is arranged alphabetically by correspondent in folders 1-11. The correspondence includes incoming letters and copies of outgoing correspondence. Correspondents include John Dunton scholars Robert Haig, S. Hodgson, Patricia Köster, and Gilbert McEwen, as well as the following repositories: the American Antiquarian Society, the British Museum, Glasgow University Library, and Union Theological Seminary.</p>
         <p>
            <ref actuate="onrequest" show="replace" target="ref24">Series II, <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
                  <part>Research Copies</part>
               </title> 
            </ref>, consists of bound and loose photocopies and photostats, and is arranged into two subseries, Primary Sources and Secondary Sources, in folders 12-21, and 24-29 (oversize). Primary Sources include two volumes of Dunton manuscripts from the Bodleian Library, Ms Rawlinson D.71 and D.72; John Dunton's will and that of his father, Rev. John Dunton; John Dunton imprints; and legal papers. Secondary Sources include a Harvard University Ph.D. dissertation, "The True Secret History of Mr. John Dunton," by Theordore Merryman Hatfield, 1926, and a few dealer catalogs.</p>
         <p>
            <ref actuate="onrequest" show="replace" target="ref54">Series III, <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
                  <part>Writings of Stephen Parks</part>
               </title> 
            </ref>, is arranged chronologically in folders 22-23. It consists of two reprints of papers by Stephen Parks, "John Dunton and <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
               <part>The Works of The Learned</part>
            </title>," and "Bookseller's Trade Sales," both published in <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
               <part>The Library</part>
            </title> (Oxford University Press, 1968, 1969).</p>  
      </scopecontent>
